<td class="mbox-image"><a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Special:Search/Pleonasm" title="wikt:Special:Search/Pleonasm"><img alt="Sister project" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Wiktionary-logo-en.svg/40px-Wiktionary-logo-en.svg.png" width="40" height="44" border="0" /></a></td>
<td class="mbox-text" style="">Look up <i><b><a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/pleonasm" class="extiw" title="wiktionary:pleonasm">pleonasm</a></b></i> in<br />
<a href="/wiki/Wiktionary" title="Wiktionary">Wiktionary</a>, the free dictionary.</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Pleonasm</b> is the use of more <a href="/wiki/Word" title="Word">words</a> (or even <a href="/wiki/Morpheme" title="Morpheme">word-parts</a>) than necessary to express an <a href="/wiki/Idea" title="Idea">idea</a> clearly. A closely related concept is <a href="/wiki/Tautology_(rhetoric)" title="Tautology (rhetoric)">rhetorical tautology</a>, in which essentially the same thing is said more than once in different words (e.g "black darkness", "cold ice", "burning fire"). Regardless, both are a form of <a href="/wiki/Redundancy_(language)" title="Redundancy (language)">redundancy</a>. <b>Pleonasm</b> and <b>tautology</b> each refer to different forms of redundancy in speech and the written word.</p>
